6860086023808, 0.058977361768484116, -0.004774937406182289, -0.0024018799886107445, -0.016473693773150444, -0.005655626766383648, 0.019983641803264618, -0.026747334748506546, -0.045398734509944916, 0.008300896733999252, 0.0009247238049283624, 0.059079840779304504, 0.01813899725675583, 0.027208495885133743, -0.01974024996161461, -0.005575564224272966, 0.008960613049566746, -0.002273779595270753, 0.016473693773150444, -0.009300079196691513, -0.002570011653006077, 0.009460204280912876, -0.0009559481986798346, 0.01974024996161461, 0.0017902011750265956, 0.012316840700805187, 0.003881437936797738, 0.0035579849500209093, -0.024620870128273964, 0.007436220534145832, -0.017690647393465042, -0.014974921010434628, 0.004973492585122585, -0.0019503264920786023, -0.010171161033213139, 0.007871760986745358, -0.019304709509015083, -0.02669609524309635, 0.0010240015108138323, 0.006987869273871183, 0.03676477447152138, -0.0030551913660019636, -0.009351319633424282, 0.031922586262226105]], "input": ["\"FLEXIBLE BUDGETS\":\"Flexible budgeting involves preparing two or more budgets using different assumptions for each about the level of sales or production. At the end of the financial period, the budget is flexed to the actual activity level for comparison to actual performance.\"", "\"FLEXED BUDGETS\":\"At the end of the year, prior to comparing the actual figures against the budget, the budgets are re-calculated (flexed) using the original budget assumptions but the actual activity levels. This means that the comparison is more valid.\"", "\"HIGH-LOW METHOD\":The High-Low Method is a technique used to calculate costs by analyzing the highest and lowest levels of activity and their associated costs. It is employed to estimate the fixed and variable components of a cost by examining these extreme activity levels and their corresponding costs. This method involves selecting the costs associated with the highest and lowest levels of activity and assuming a straight-line relationship between these two points. By doing so, it helps in estimating the fixed and variable elements of a semi-variable cost, enabling more accurate forecasts of costs. Specifically, the High-Low Method calculates the variable overhead cost per unit by taking the difference in costs at the highest and lowest levels of activity and dividing it by the difference in activity levels.", "\"LEARNING CURVE\":The concept of the \"Learning Curve\" represents the rate at which individuals or groups improve their performance with experience. It is commonly used in budgeting to predict how costs will decrease as production increases. Graphically, a learning curve illustrates how an increase in learning comes from greater experience; the more frequently a task is performed, the better and more efficient the individual becomes at it, resulting in reduced time to complete the task.\n\nThe learning curve concept specifically refers to the reduction in time taken to produce each unit as workers gain more experience, leading to increased efficiency and reduced costs over time. This is often expressed as a percentage, indicating the rate at which learning and efficiency improve. For example, in the production of Parapain, which is extremely difficult to handle, an 80% learning curve exists. This means that the time taken to produce the drug decreases as more batches are produced, up to the first 1,000 batches.\n\nOverall, the learning curve is a valuable tool for estimating the learning rate and learning effect, providing a graphical representation of how the time required to perform a task decreases with increasing repetitions.", "\"ADVANTAGES OF FLEXIBLE BUDGETS\":\"The requirement to prepare more than one fixed budget means that managers are required to consider a range of forecasts, and actual results can be compared more meaningfully against the budget for the closest level of activity.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF FLEXIBLE BUDGETS\":\"Difficulty in separating fixed and variable elements of indirect costs (overheads), and cost may not behave as assumed (e.g., linearly or as predicted by a learning curve).\"", "\"FLEXED PRODUCTION COST QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the flexed total production cost for production at 80% of maximum capacity for Corfe Co, which manufactures computer laptop batteries.\"", "\"OBJECTIVES OF A BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\":\"The main objectives of a budgetary control system are planning, coordination of the activities of the organisation, and ensuring better resource utilisation.\"", "\"ROLLING BUDGET\":\"ROLLING BUDGET\" is a continuous budgeting process where the budget is updated regularly, typically every quarter, to reflect changes in the market and business environment. This approach is more flexible and responsive to changes compared to traditional annual budgets. A rolling budget is continuously updated and is most suitable in a rapidly changing environment where the original budget quickly becomes outdated.", "\"ACTIVITY-BASED BUDGETING (ABB)\":\"Activity-based budgets use ABC principles to calculate the budgeted overhead costs.\"", "\"BEYOND BUDGETING MODEL\":\"The Beyond Budgeting model aims to replace traditional budgetary control systems with a more modern approach which replaces financial targets with key performance indicators.\"", "\"CORRELATION\":\"Correlation\" is an analysis technique used to measure the strength and direction of the relationship between two variables. It refers to the closeness of the relationship between two or more variables and can be positive, negative, perfect, or zero, indicating the degree to which variables move together.", "\"REGRESSION\":\"Regression\" is an analysis technique used to model the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. Specifically, regression analysis is used to forecast the value of one variable based on the value of another by assuming a linear relationship described by the equation y = a + bx. The values of a and b in this equation can be determined using the least squares regression method.", "\"TIME SERIES ANALYSIS\":\"Time series analysis\" involves analyzing data points collected or recorded at specific time intervals to identify trends, cycles, and seasonal variations. It can be applied to any figures that vary over time, including sales, production, and costs. The main components of a time series are trend, seasonal variations, cyclical variations, and random variations.", "\"GEOMETRIC MEAN\":\"The geometric mean is used to calculate average growth rates and is most commonly used in business and finance to calculate growth rates in percentages. It is calculated as the nth root of the product of n numbers.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF GEOMETRIC MEAN\":\"The sales of Beta during the last three years were as follows: Year Sales in $000 20X2 100 20X3 180 20X4 210 20X5 300. The growth rate of sales each year is as follows: 20X3 80% (180 - 100)/100 20X4 16.67% (210 - 180)/180 20X5 42.9% (300 - 210)/210. The simple average growth rate is 46.5%, calculated as (80% + 16.67% + 42.9%)/3. However, this overstates the rate of growth: If the 20X2 sales of $100,000 were to increase by 46.5% each year for three years, the sales in 20X5 would be $314,000, not $300,000. The more accurate growth rate is obtained using the geometric mean. This is used to calculate average growth rates and is most commonly used in business and finance to calculate growth rates in percentages. Growing by 80% is the same as multiplying by 1.8, so the geometric mean for the three years is cube root(1.8 * 1.1667 * 1.429) = 1.442, so the average growth rate is 44.2%. This can then be used to calculate expected sales in future periods.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}